<DOC><DOCNO> AP890212-0001 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-02-12-89 2346EST</FILEID><FIRST>u i AM-Angola-SouthAfrica 1stLd-Writethru a0810 02-12 0423</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Angola-South Africa, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0810,0433</SECOND><HEAD>Angola Claims South African Troops Violated Peace Accord</HEAD><HEAD>Eds: Leads with 2 grafs to note that report monitored in Lisbon;picks up 3rd graf `The Pretoria...'</HEAD><DATELINE>LISBON, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Angola said its troops killed 40 SouthAfrican soldiers who crossed the border, violating a regional peaceagreement, the Angolan news agency ANGOP reported Sunday.   The Marxist government protested to South Africa about theincident that also left seven Angolan soldiers dead, said the reportmonitored in Lisbon.   The Pretoria government rejected the charge and requested animmediate meeting of a commission monitoring the peace accord todiscuss the matter.   The Angolan Defense Ministry statement issued Saturday said SouthAfrican troops on Wednesday crossed into Angola from neighboringNamibia in support of Angolan rebels, ANGOP reported.   The Angolan government troops drove the South Africans back tothe Namibian frontier after heavy fighting that ended early Friday,ANGOP reported. It said 40 South African soldiers were   In Pretoria, the South African Foreign Affairs Department said itreplied ``in the strongest terms'' to the allegations contained in aprotest note sent by Angola's government.   In the statement Sunday, South Africa said it was on standby toattend an urgent meeting of the monitoring commission in Luanda, theAngolan capital, to discuss Angola's allegations.   The U.S. State Department said last week it had no evidence thatany South African troops entered Angola.   South African military authorities say their forces are strictlyobserving the U.S.-brokered peace agreement signed in December. Theagreement bars South African military aid to the anti-Marxist rebelsin Angola and calls for independence of Namibia from South Africancontrol.   The peace accord established a joint commission, comprised ofSouth African, Cuban and Angolan representatives, to monitorobservance of the various provisions.   As part of the peace agreement, about 50,000 Cuban troops were towithdraw from Angola, where they have been helping the governmentfight the rebels belonging to the National Union for the TotalIndependence of Angola.   The rebel group rejects the peace accords and has vowed tocontinue fighting until the Angolan government agrees to share power.   The area where the fighting reportedly took place is near astretch of the border between Angola and Namibia which does not havemonitoring posts called for in the peace agreement.   The rebels said Saturday that 275 government soldiers died inheavy fighting last week when 4,000 guerrillas clashed with theAngolan army in southern Cuando Cubango province.   The rebels denied South African troops participated in thefighting.</TEXT></DOC>